GIT INTRODUCTION

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in code.
It helps developers collaborate on projects and maintain different versions of the code.

Git allows developers to work on the same project without overwriting each other’s work.

WHY GIT IS USED

track changes in code

collaborate with multiple developers

maintain different versions of a project

revert back to previous versions if needed

GIT VS GITHUB

Git is a tool used to track code changes locally.

GitHub is a cloud platform used to store Git repositories and collaborate with other developers.

Git works on the local machine while GitHub stores code remotely.

COMMON GIT COMMANDS

git init
used to initialize a new git repository

git status
shows the current status of files in the repository

git add
adds files to the staging area

example
git add file.txt

git commit
saves the changes with a message

example
git commit -m "initial commit"

git log
shows the history of commits

STAGES IN GIT

working directory
files are created or modified here

staging area
files are added here before committing

repository
committed files are stored permanently here

CONNECTING LOCAL REPO TO GITHUB

first create a repository on GitHub.

Then run the following commands:

git remote add origin repository_url

git branch -M main

git push -u origin main

This pushes the local code to GitHub.

WHAT I PRACTICED TODAY

installed git

created a local repository

added files using git add

committed changes using git commit

pushed code to github